And just like that … I fell in love. ❤️ On National Puppy Day, I present my new baby! Last week, we featured four “Golden Girls” from Golden Treasures Rescue who are in desperate need of foster homes and “furever” homes for Golden Retrievers rescued from puppy mills. I fell in love with all four babies … but the Angel sitting to my right … did me in with that first sweet kiss. After completing my online application, interview, meet and greet play date with my Bruno, and the rest of the adoption process, my 8 month old baby girl arrived! I can’t thank her foster mom Cathy and her family for taking such wonderful care of her for the last four months … and for all the incredible training too! Wow! She is such a gift and treasure to my family! And she has helped to heal my heart in so many ways! Thank you also to Sandy of Golden Treasures  Rescue and to Kim, Erin, Cathy and Sonny for coming on our show. And a huge thank you to my wonderful producers Margaret and Darren for booking this segment. They clearly knew what they we doing… and worked their magic! 😉 I am so grateful 🙏🥹 she has brought so much life and laughter back into my home! ❤️ but now … I need your help! The kids and I have discussed hundreds of names …topping the list - Belle and Dolly! Please help!

social_posts.post_text: Here’s  to the BEST crew ever! This Fox 8 Family is greatest! Thank you all for your impeccable planning, hustle and dedication to make this remote live  show Top Notch! I love you all so much! @fox8newscleveland

I am so grateful for this amazing woman! Mom… I have never met another person with a more compassionate and tender heart. You have and will ALWAYS be my role model. Everyone who has met you LOVES you … and I am so thankful that I get YOU as my mom! Thank you for also being the greatest Grandmother to Siena and Race! You truly ARE one in a million! Happy Mother’s Day! I love you … most! ❤️

I wanted to fill all of you in on why I have not been at Fox 8 the last two weeks. I was doing yard work a few weekends ago and took a giant step over the wall of bushes (that are pictured behind me in this photo). I was installing a new water pump in my birdbath, and when I stepped over the bush to get back on the concrete patio, I stepped right on a plastic rock solar light, and it just slid straight out with my foot on it. My other leg was still back behind the bush and I ended up landing on the concrete in a complete straddle split position. I knew immediately that I had a pretty bad injury. (I heard and felt pops and tears) Turns out, I completely - 100% tore my entire hamstring straight off of my pelvic bone. (Called a Complete Avulsion Tear). This is such a rare injury that there are only a few doctors in the country who do this delicate and tricky surgery. And thank God, Dr. James Rosneck of the Cleveland Clinic sports medicine team (and Cavaliers team doc) is one of the best in the country and did my surgery last Thursday.  I am unable to walk or have any weight bearing on my right leg for six weeks to two months or quite possibly much longer. I am also unable to sit normally, except for if I sit on my left hip because of the incision location and all of the repair that is in my right pelvic back area. This will be a long, painful and slow process to begin walking again. Through all of this, I am very very anxious to get back to work. I miss being with my Fox 8 family so much… and I miss all of YOU so much!  I am also unable to drive for several weeks/months and we are just figuring out how I would be able to get up on the anchor set at work and be in a protected and safe situation considering I can only use a wheelchair and crutches. I am doing everything I can to get back on the air on Fox8. Thank You to Fox 8 for being so understanding and supportive during this awful time for me. I can’t wait to get back on the air! And I will continue to update you through my very slow and tedious progress! ❤️
Rest in peace Jim Brown ❤️🙏 Monique … you and your beautiful children are in my prayers 🙏❤️
Everyone needs a Gina 🩷 I am so thankful for this Angel on earth!  I love you! 💕

I want thank the incredible staff at the Cleveland Clinic sports medicine facility, Cleveland Clinic ER and Hillcrest ER. I was so well cared for over the last three weeks by so many incredibly loving and compassionate and highly skilled medical professionals. Thank you Dr Victor Krebs, Dr James Rosneck, Kristen Banjac, Andrew Mindeck, Elizabeth and Bailey (my awesome ambulance paramedics), nurse Tobanno, Dr Hughes, Dr Sauso, Amanda, Jason and crew with Cleveland Police Department and the Cleveland Clinic PD, nurses Karen, Sarah, Gayle, Martha, Sarah S, my ER Doctor at Hillcrest and orthopedic resident at Hillcrest and my wonderful anesthesiologists. And now to my physical therapist Matthew … you have the task of bringing it all together and helping me walk again! PUSH ME! I am SO ready to push through! I’m so sorry if I did not include your name because they were so many of you! My little guardian angels surrounding me over these last three weeks and giving me such wonderful care! You are all in the profession you were BORN to be in! ❤️
One of the biggest struggles through this is that I have to rely on my loved ones for EVERY SINGLE THING. My mom and daughter Siena have been by my side nonstop ❤️ I am so used to doing to everything for everyone around me… that this has really been a tough adjustment. I am reminded by my sweet children Siena and Race that I did have a split decision, as I was falling - to not just fall back but rather ride out what was going to happen with my leg. I did what I could to protect my head, and this was the safest and least catastrophic decision that I could make in an instant…and I’m grateful I did.  So when I am feeling helpless and sad… I have to remind myself to feel grateful. As I have learned over the last 11+ years…  do everything you can to protect your head. It has been ingrained in my life and my kids. We feel those gentle reminders from our Roger who is in our hearts all the time. ❤️ so much to be thankful for.

The worst part of my injury and surgery was that I missed my son Race’s graduation from Villanova University. I was crushed. His graduation was Friday, and I was in too bad of shape to travel to Philadelphia. Besides blood clot risks, it was too soon after surgery - and as much as I tried to push myself, I just could not make the trip. I was devastated and heartbroken. I have raised my children myself since my husbands accident for over 11 years - it was just inconceivable to me to not be there. But I couldn’t. And it crushed me. Of course Race understood completely- we had been FaceTiming me a few times a day and was well aware of my limitations and the impossibility of traveling. So… on Friday, my mom helped put on my Villanova gear … and together we Live-Streamed graduation …on the couch. Bawling our eyes out. I am so PROUD of this amazing young man and all that he has accomplished… but I could not be there to support him … and hug him… and experience his graduation. Ugh. 😔😨🥺 It was just the best - and worst feeling. We had three days of events planned surrounding graduation - the school Mass, his Basketball banquet, dinners with his friends and their families, moving him out of his house etc. And missing all of this just crushed my heart. BUT… today is a new day… and last night he came home! My daughter Siena is still here from Los Angeles helping to take care of me … so right now my heart is so full. ❤️
(Thank you @kickinitwithkenny for giving me the greatest Pep Talk known to mankind as I was bawling my eyes out Friday morning). @race_d_

6 months ago today, I fell while working outside on my patio and pulled my right hamstring completely off my pelvic bone. (Called a complete avulsion tear) and pulled both groin muscles. Today, I met with my surgeon, Dr. James Rosneck and saw my physical therapist Matthew - and they cleared me! Incredibly, I was about two months ahead of schedule with my recovery - mainly because we were able to do the surgery within a few days of the injury, but mostly because Dr Rosneck is one of the best surgeons in the world! And a lot was the physical therapy - with Matthew at the Cleveland Clinic - and the hours of daily therapy I did at home. I WAS DETERMINED to get better! I am absolutely so blown away with how quickly this has all come together - and how because of my incredible, supportive medical team, my amazing mom and kids - and precious friends, I am pretty close to where I was before my injury. Definitely not going to ski, skate or sprint anytime soon … but for now, I am enjoying every single step that I walk and so grateful and appreciative to God for His miraculous healing wonders!

This weekend we lost our precious Marco.  Our hearts are just broken and aching for him. Marco and his brother Polo were rescues and were my son’s birthday gift 15 years ago. Marco had the greatest - and funniest personality I’ve ever seen in a cat. He acted more like a little dog - and was ALWAYS around and part of the action in the house. He was just so darling and so lovable. He was also so comforting to not just us humans, but to his brother Polo and to Bruno and Gunner, and now to Belle. Marco, thank you for a million laughs, 15 years of snuggles and endless love. I ache for you. The Rainbow Bridge gained an Angel, and I know Gunner is so happy to have you snuggle with him again. I promise you that Siena, Race and I will take wonderful loving care of your brother, best friend and soulmate Polo. And I promise I will keep the bird feeders full for your little friends. 🙏❤️ my little buddy… you were a treasure
